Question 21

You didn't Attempt

The minimal expression for PQ + P'QR + P'QR'S is ____.

PQ + QR + QS

Correct answer

P+R+S

Q

None

Solution

Hide

PQ + P'QR + P'QR'S

= Q(P+P'R + P'R'S)

= Q( (P +P')(P +R) + P'S) 

= Q( P +R + P'S) 

= Q( (P + P')(P+S) + R)

= Q(P  + S + R)

= PQ + QS + QR

Question 23

You didn't Attempt

Match List 1 with List 2 and choose the correct answer from the code given below:

Where V and E are the number of vertices and edges in graph respectively.

(a)-(i), (b)-(iii), (c)-(iv), (d)-(ii)

(a)-(i), (b)-(iii), (c)-(ii), (d)-(iv)

(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(ii), (d)-(iv)

Correct answer

(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(iv), (d)-(ii)

Solution

Hide

Dijkstra's algorithm (or Dijkstra's Shortest Path First algorithm, SPF algorithm) is an algorithm for finding the shortest paths between nodes in a graph and time complexity is O(V2).

Kruskal's algorithm is a minimum-spanning-tree algorithm which finds an edge of the least possible weight that connects any two trees in the forest and time complexity is O(E log E).

A topological sort or topological ordering of a directed graph is a linear ordering of its vertices such that for every directed edge uv from vertex u to vertex v,u comes before v in the ordering (V + E).

Consider implementation of stack using queue by following algorithm. Let x be an element to be pushed in the stack.

push(q1, x) {

   EQ(q1,x)

   size = q1.size();

   while (size > 1) {

k= DQ(q1)

EQ(q1,k)

size--;

          }

}

pop(q1) {

   DQ(q1)

}

How many enqueue and dequeue operations required to perform 3 push and 1 pop sequentially in an empty stack?

6EQ, 3DQ

5EQ, 5DQ

4EQ, 2DQ

6EQ, 4DQ

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

To push 3 elements say a,b,c, sequence of operations will be:

EQ(a) -> EQ (b) -> DQ(a) ->EQ(a) -> EQ(c)->DQ(b)-> EQ(b)-> DQ(a) -> EQ(a)

= 6EQ, 3DQ

To pop 1 elements = 1 DQ

Total = 6EQ, 4DQ

Question 50

You didn't Attempt

Consider the following page table. All numbers in the table are binary

Assume that the virtual addresses are 12bits long. The physical address of the virtual address 001100000010 is

001000000110

001100000010

000000000010

Correct answer

Invalid Address

Solution

Hide

The logical address 00110000001 is divided into a 4-bit page number and an 8-bit offset. Thus, 00110000001 has its 4-bit page number 001 and offset 0000001. Because the page number 001 has its page frame in frame 000, the physical address is 00000000001.

Question 53

You didn't Attempt

Consider a file currently consisting of 50 blocks. Assume that the file-control block (and the index block, in the case of indexed allocation) is already in memory. In the contiguous-allocation case, assume that there is no room to grow at the beginning but there is room to grow at the end. Also assume that the block information to be added is stored in memory. Calculate how many disk I/O operations are required for contiguous, linked, and indexed (single-level) allocation strategies, if a block is removed from the beginning.

201, 1, 1

101, 52, 1

1, 3, 1

98, 1,0

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

i. Contiguous: The remaining 49 blocks are moved forward and each move requires 1 read and 1 write, The total number of disk I/O operations is 98 = 2 49.

ii. Linked: Read the first block to find the second one. The second blocks address is used to update the directory of this file. Hence, only 1 disk I/O operation is needed.

iii. Indexed: Shifting the addresses stored in the index block one position upward does not need any disk I/O operation.

Question 54

You didn't Attempt

Consider a system having m resources of the same type. These resources are shared by 3 processes A, B, C which have peak time demands of 3, 4, 6 respectively. The minimum value of m that ensures deadlock will never occur is

11

Correct answer

12

13

14

Solution

Hide

If A has 2, B has 3, C has 5 then a deadlock will occur i.e., 2+3+5=10.

If we have one extra resource then a deadlock will not occur i.e., 10+1=11.

If we have equal (or) more than 11 resources then deadlock will never occur.

Question 56

You didn't Attempt

A 2-way set associative cache is 512 Kbytes in size. How many bits are needed for the set number, block offset respectively in the physical address if block size is 64 Byte

-

Your answer

12

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Physical address in a set associative cache has three fields: (tag bits + set number + block offset).

Number of Blocks =512K / 64 = 2^19 / 2^6 = 2^13

Number of sets = 2^13 / 2 = 2^12

 No. of bits needed for set number = 12

Question 63

You didn't Attempt

A file system with 300 GByte disk uses a file descriptor with 8 direct block addresses, 1 indirect block address and 1 doubly indirect block address. The size of each disk block is 256 Bytes and the size of each disk block address is 8 Bytes. The maximum possible file size in this file system is

3 KBytes

35 KBytes

266 KBytes

Correct answer

dependent on the size of the disk

Solution

Hide

Its given disk block is of size 256B.

So, one direct block addressing will point to 8 disk blocks = 8*256 B = 2 KB

Singly Indirect block addressing will point to 1 disk block which has 256/8 disc block addresses = (256/8)*256 B = 8 KB

Doubly indirect block addressing will point to 1 disk block which has 256/8 addresses to disk blocks which in turn has 256/8 addresses to disk blocks  = 32*32*256 B = 256 KB

Maximum possible file size = 2 KB + 8 KB + 256 KB = 266 KB

Question 64

You didn't Attempt

#include<stdio.h>

int main ()

{

int i=5;

if (--i)

{

main ();

printf("%d",i);

}

}

What will be the output of the above program?

54321

4321

Compile time error

Segmentation Fault

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

For the above program, the output will be a Segmentation fault, because of a stack overflow. Your recursion never finishes.

I will be initialized to 5 after every main () function call. and it will be decremented to 4 in the if condition. But it will never become zero.

Hence 4 will print until stack overflow and finally program execution will terminate, by giving Segmentation Fault.
